    <strong>Example 1</strong>
    <br>
    Simplify (-2) – (-4)
    <br>
    <strong>Solution </strong>
    <br>
    (-2) – (-4) = -2 + 4 = <strong>+2</strong>
    <br>
    <strong>The above means you owe 2 (i.e. -2) and have 4 (i.e. +4), if you pay the 2, you will still have 2 with you (i.e. +2).</strong> 
    <br>
    <strong>Generally</strong> in directed numbers addition and subtraction;
    <br>
    (i)	If the larger number has the negative sign (-) before it, the result is negative (-).
    <br>
    (ii)	If the larger number has the positive sign (+) before it, the result is positive (+).
    <br>
    (iii)	If the signs are the same, disregard the sign and add the two numbers, therefore;
    <br>
    <span class='ml-5'>(i)	If both signs are positive (+), the result is positive (+)</span>
    <br>
    <span class='ml-5'>(ii)	If both signs are negative (-), the result is negative (-)</span>
    <br>
    <strong>The above can be used to simplify the directed numbers easily without stress.</strong>
    </p>
    <div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
    <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Multiplication of Directed Numbers </h3>
    </div>
    <p class='ml-3'>
     <strong>Multiplication</strong> means to increase the number. It is also regarded as repeated addition e.g. 3 x 3 = 3 + 3 + 3 = <strong>9</strong>
    </p>
    <div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
    <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Positive Multipliers in Directed Numbers</h3>
    </div>
    <p class='ml-3'>
    <strong>General rules for positive multipliers;</strong>
    <br>
    (+i) x (+j) = <strong>+ (i x j) i.e. + x + = + </strong>
    <br>
    (+i) x (-j) = <strong>- (i x j) i.e. + x - = - </strong>
    <br>
     <strong>Example 1</strong>
     <br>
     Simplify the following; (i) (+8) x (+4) (ii) (+12) x (-2) (iii) (+<sup>2</sup>&frasl;<sub>3</sub>) x (+<sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>3</sub>) (iv) 3 x (-0.6)
     <br>
     <strong>Solution</strong>
     <br>
    (i) (+8) x (+4) = + (8 x 4)  = <strong> +32 </strong>
      <br>
    (ii) (+12) x (-2) = - (12 x 2) = <strong>-24</strong>
      <br>
    (iii) (+<sup>2</sup>&frasl;<sub>3</sub>) x (+<sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>3</sub>) = + ( <sup>2</sup>&frasl;<sub>3</sub> x  <sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>3</sub>) = <strong> +<sup>2</sup>&frasl;<sub>9</sub> </strong>
      <br>
    (iv)  3 x (-0.6) = - (3 x 0.6) = <strong>-1.8</strong>
    </p>
  
    <div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
    <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'> Negative Multipliers in Directed Numbers </h3>
    </div>
    <p class='ml-3'>
  
    <strong>General rules for negative multipliers;</strong>
    <br>
    (-i) x (+j) = <strong>- (i x j) i.e. - x + = -</strong>
    <br>
    (-i) x (-j) = <strong>+ (i x j) i.e. - x - = +</strong>
    <br>
    <strong>Example 1</strong>
    <br>
   Simplify (i) (-2) x (+4) (ii) (-16) x (-3) (iii) (-<sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>4</sub>) x (+<sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>2</sub>) (iv) (-6) X (-0.5)
   <br>
   <strong>Solution</strong>
   <br>
    (-2) x (+4) = - (2 x 4) = <strong>-8</strong>
    <br>
    (-16) x (-3) = + (16 x 3) = <strong>+48</strong>
    <br>
    (-<sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>4</sub>) x (+<sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>2</sub>) =  -(<sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>4</sub> x (<sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>2</sub>)= <strong> -<sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>8</sub></strong>
    <br>
    (-6) X (-0.5) = + (6 x 0.5) = <strong>+3</strong>
    <br>
   <strong>Note:</strong> when multiplying directed numbers;
   <br>
    <span  class='ml-3'>(i) Two like signs give a positive result(+)</span>
    <br>
    <span  class='ml-3'>(ii) Two unlike signs or different signs give a negative result(-)</span>
  </p>
  <div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
    <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'> Division in Directed Numbers </h3>
  </div>
  <p class='ml-3'>
  <strong>Divide</strong> means to share or to find how many times a number is contained in another number.
  <br>
  In general;
  <br>
    (+i) ÷ (+j) = <strong>+(<sup>i</sup>&frasl;<sub>j</sub>)</strong>
    <br>
    (-i) ÷ (-j) =<strong> +(<sup>i</sup>&frasl;<sub>j</sub>) </strong>
    <br>
    (+i) ÷ (-j) = <strong>-(<sup>i</sup>&frasl;<sub>j</sub>)</strong>
    <br>
    (-i) ÷ (+j) = <strong>-(<sup>i</sup>&frasl;<sub>j</sub>)</strong>
  <br>
  <strong>In mathematics; by => ÷ and of => ×.</strong>
  <br>
  <strong>Example 1</strong>
  <br>
  Simplify the following; (i) (+36) ÷ (+12) (ii) (-16) ÷ (-4) (iii) (-36) ÷ (+18) (iv) (+9) ÷ (-27)
  <br>
  <strong>Solution</strong>
  <br>
    (i) (+36) ÷ (+12) = +(<sup>336</sup>&frasl;<sub>13</sub>) = <strong>+3</strong>
    <br>
    (ii) (-16) ÷ (-4) = +(<sup>16</sup>&frasl;<sub>4</sub>) = <strong>+4</strong>
    <br>
    (iii) (-36) ÷ (+18) = -(<sup>36</sup>&frasl;<sub>18</sub>) = <strong>-2</strong>
    <br>
    (iii) (+9) ÷ (-27) = -(<sup>9</sup>&frasl;<sub>27</sub>) = <strong>-(<sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>3</sub>)</strong>
    <br>
  <strong>Example 2</strong>
  <br>
  Solve <sup>(-7) x (-4) </sup>&frasl;<sub>(-2)</sub>
  <br>
  <strong>Solution</strong>
  <br>
  <sup>(-7) x (-4) </sup>&frasl;<sub>(-2)</sub> = <sup>(+28)</sup>&frasl;<sub>(-2)</sub> = - <sup>28</sup>&frasl;<sub>2</sub> = <strong>-14</strong>
  </p>
  </article>
